The paper deals with a wireless communication network with energy harvesting, which falls under the domain of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The use of random walk theory and stochastic geometry suggests a mathematical approach, which is also relevant to machine learning (cs.MA) and game theory (cs.GT). The analysis of the energy utilization rate and hitting/stopping time analysis suggests a control systems perspective, which is relevant to systems and control (cs.SY).
